<http://dx.doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4511.1.1>
    bibo:endPage "193" ;
    bibo:issue "1" ;
    bibo:journal "Zootaxa" ;
    bibo:pubDate "2018-11-05" ;
    bibo:startPage "1" ;
    bibo:volume "4511" ;
    dc:creator "Orr, Michael C.; Pitts, James P.; Griswold, Terry" ;
    dc:date "2018" ;
    dc:title "Revision of the bee group Anthophora (Micranthophora) (Hymenoptera: Apidae), with notes on potential conservation concerns and a molecular phylogeny of the genus" ;
    fabio:hasPart <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3771093>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3771083>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770981>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770989>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770991> ;
    a fabio:JournalArticle .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3771093>
    dc:description "FIGURE 54. Male habitus of A) Anthophora abroniae (BBSL502223), B) A. albata (10046), C) A. caudata (BBSLID92552), D) A. chihuahua (BBSL502617), E) A. cockerelli (72472), F) A. columbariae (BBSL853157). Scale=1 mm." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/3771093/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3771083>
    dc:description "FIGURE 49. Male face of A) Anthophora abroniae (BBSL502212), B) A. albata (BBSL504186), C) A. caudata (BBSLID98988), D) A. chihuahua (BBSL502617), E) A. cockerelli (BBSL502260), F) A. columbariae (BBSL853110). Scale=0.5 mm." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/3771083/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770981>
    dc:description "FIGURE 1. All collection localities represented in this study. Level 1 admin areas are given and each black circle represents a site where at least one species has been collected, often numerous (the maximum number of species collected at one site is six)." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/3770981/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770989>
    dc:description "FIGURE 4. Number of species per state. Darker background colors indicate higher species richness, based on ranges given in the legend. The center of species richness is quite clearly in the deserts of southwestern North America." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/3770989/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770991>
    dc:description "FIGURE 5. Number of species per ecoregion. The ten ecoregions with the highest species richness are as follows, with the number of species and specimens given in parentheses: Mojave Desert (21; 2589), Sonoran Desert (19; 2441), Great Basin shrub steppe (14; 1303), California coastal sage and chaparral (13; 661), California montane chaparral and woodlands (13; 196), Colorado Plateau shrublands (11; 3279), Sierra Nevada forests (8; 288), Baja California desert (8; 64); Chihuahuan Desert (7; 1240), Snake-Columbia shrub steppe (6; 207). 48 additional ecoregions are inhabited by various A. (Micranthophora), given in their respective species accounts." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/3770991/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

